# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ciliate
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:ciliate/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:ciliate/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:ciliate/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:ciliate/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:ciliate/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:ciliate/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:ciliate/aconoidasida] The **Aconoidasida** are a class of apicomplexan parasites described by Mehlhorn *et al* in 1980.
[src:ciliate/aconoidasida] Organisms in this class bear a tip at one end of their outer membrane.
[src:ciliate/aconoidasida] This apical complex includes vesicles called rhoptries and micronemes, which open at the anterior of the cell.
[src:ciliate/aconoidasida] These secrete enzymes that allow the parasite to enter other cells.
[src:ciliate/aconoidasida] The tip is surrounded by a band of microtubules, called the polar ring.
[src:ciliate/aconoidasida] As the name indicates, Aconoidasida (from Greek: negative prefix *a-* = "lacking") lack a conoid (they do have one only during the ookinete stage) in contrast to the class Conoidasida which have one throughout their life cycle.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:ciliate/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:ciliate/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] This genus was named in 1999 by Fernández and collaborators.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] The species in this genus are fusiform with an apical anterior concavity and a longitudinal groove.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] There are two anterior flagellae directed backward.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] The flagellae arise from parallel basal bodies in a flagellar pocket.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] The single nucleus has a single nucleolus.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] The cell wall is a trilaminate pellicle with subpellicular microtubules and a micropore.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] The cytoplasm contains a single, branched mitochondrion with tubular cristae, a supranuclear Golgi apparatus and large amounts of glycan granules.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] There are three types of secretory organelles present.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] Type I are round and structurally complex.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] The types II and III appear to be rhoptry and microneme like organelles respectively.
[src:ciliate/acrocoelus] The type species is *Acrocoelus glossobalani* I.Fernández, Pardos, Jes.Benito & N.L.Arroyo, 1999.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The **ciliates** are a group of alveolates characterized by the presence of hair-like organelles called cilia, which are identical in structure to eukaryotic flagella, but are in general shorter and present in much larger numbers, with a different undulating pattern than flagella.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Cilia occur in all members of the group (although the peculiar Suctoria only have them for part of their life cycle) and are variously used in swimming, crawling, attachment, feeding, and sensation.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Ciliates are an important group of protists, common almost anywhere there is water—in lakes, ponds, oceans, rivers, and wet soils, including anoxic (oxygen-depleted) habitats.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] About 4,500 unique free-living species have been described, and the potential number of extant species is estimated at 27,000–40,000.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Included in this number are many ectosymbiotic and endosymbiotic species, as well as some obligate and opportunistic parasites.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Ciliate species range in size from as little as 10 μm in some colpodeans to as much as 4 mm in length in some geleiids, and include some of the most morphologically complex protozoans.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In most systems of taxonomy, "**Ciliophora**" is ranked as a phylum under any of several kingdoms, including Chromista, Protista or Protozoa.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In some older systems of classification, such as the influential taxonomic works of Alfred Kahl, ciliated protozoa are placed within the class "**Ciliata**" (a term which can also refer to a genus of fish).
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In the taxonomic scheme endorsed by the International Society of Protistologists, which eliminates formal rank designations such as "phylum" and "class", "Ciliophora" is an unranked taxon within Alveolata.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The latter is generated from the micronucleus by amplification of the genome and heavy editing.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The micronucleus passes its genetic material to offspring, but does not express its genes.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The macronucleus provides the small nuclear RNA for vegetative growth.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Division of the macronucleus occurs in most ciliate species, apart from those in class Karyorelictea, whose macronuclei are replaced every time the cell divides.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Macronuclear division is accomplished by amitosis, and the segregation of the chromosomes occurs by a process whose mechanism is unknown.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] After a certain number of generations (200–350, in *Paramecium aurelia*, and as many as 1,500 in *Tetrahymena*) the cell shows signs of aging, and the macronuclei must be regenerated from the micronuclei.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Usually, this occurs following *conjugation*, after which a new macronucleus is generated from the post-conjugal micronucleus.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Food vacuoles are formed through phagocytosis and typically follow a particular path through the cell as their contents are digested and broken down by lysosomes so the substances the vacuole contains are then small enough to diffuse through the membrane of the food vacuole into the cell.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Anything left in the food vacuole by the time it reaches the cytoproct (anal pore) is discharged by exocytosis.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Most ciliates also have one or more prominent contractile vacuoles, which collect water and expel it from the cell to maintain osmotic pressure, or in some function to maintain ionic balance.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In some genera, such as *Paramecium*, these have a distinctive star shape, with each point being a collecting tube.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Mostly, body cilia are arranged in *mono-* and *dikinetids*, which respectively include one and two kinetosomes (basal bodies), each of which may support a cilium.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] These are arranged into rows called *kineties*, which run from the anterior to posterior of the cell.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The body and oral kinetids make up the *infraciliature*, an organization unique to the ciliates and important in their classification, and include various fibrils and microtubules involved in coordinating the cilia.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In some forms there are also body polykinetids, for instance, among the spirotrichs where they generally form bristles called cirri.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The infraciliature is one of the main components of the cell cortex.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Others are the *alveoli*, small vesicles under the cell membrane that are packed against it to form a pellicle maintaining the cell's shape, which varies from flexible and contractile to rigid.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Numerous mitochondria and extrusomes are also generally present.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The presence of alveoli, the structure of the cilia, the form of mitosis and various other details indicate a close relationship between the ciliates, Apicomplexa, and dinoflagellates.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] These superficially dissimilar groups make up the alveolates.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Most ciliates are heterotrophs, feeding on smaller organisms, such as bacteria and algae, and detritus swept into the oral groove (mouth) by modified oral cilia.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] This usually includes a series of membranelles to the left of the mouth and a paroral membrane to its right, both of which arise from *polykinetids*, groups of many cilia together with associated structures.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The food is moved by the cilia through the mouth pore into the gullet, which forms food vacuoles.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Many species are also mixotrophic, combining phagotrophy and phototrophy through kleptoplasty or symbiosis with photosynthetic microbes.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The ciliate *Halteria* has been observed to feed on chloroviruses.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Feeding techniques vary considerably, however.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Some ciliates are mouthless and feed by absorption (osmotrophy), while others are predatory and feed on other protozoa and in particular on other ciliates.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Some ciliates parasitize animals, although only one species, *Balantidium coli*, is known to cause disease in humans.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Ciliates reproduce asexually, by various kinds of fission.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] During fission, the micronucleus undergoes mitosis and the macronucleus elongates and undergoes amitosis (except among the Karyorelictean ciliates, whose macronuclei do not divide).
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The cell then divides in two, and each new cell obtains a copy of the micronucleus and the macronucleus.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Typically, the cell is divided transversally, with the anterior half of the ciliate (the *proter*) forming one new organism, and the posterior half (the *opisthe*) forming another.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] However, other types of fission occur in some ciliate groups.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] These include *budding* (the emergence of small ciliated offspring, or "swarmers", from the body of a mature parent); *strobilation* (multiple divisions along the cell body, producing a chain of new organisms); and *palintomy* (multiple fissions, usually within a cyst).
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Fission may occur spontaneously, as part of the vegetative cell cycle.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Alternatively, it may proceed as a result of self-fertilization (autogamy), or it may follow conjugation, a sexual phenomenon in which ciliates of compatible mating types exchange genetic material.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] While conjugation is sometimes described as a form of reproduction, it is not directly connected with reproductive processes, and does not directly result in an increase in the number of individual ciliates or their progeny.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Ciliate conjugation is a sexual phenomenon that results in genetic recombination and nuclear reorganization within the cell.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] During conjugation, two ciliates of a compatible mating type form a bridge between their cytoplasms.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The micronuclei undergo meiosis, the macronuclei disappear, and haploid micronuclei are exchanged over the bridge.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In some ciliates (peritrichs, chonotrichs and some suctorians), conjugating cells become permanently fused, and one conjugant is absorbed by the other.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In most ciliate groups, however, the cells separate after conjugation, and both form new macronuclei from their micronuclei.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Conjugation and autogamy are always followed by fission.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In many ciliates, such as *Paramecium*, conjugating partners (gamonts) are similar or indistinguishable in size and shape.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] This is referred to as "isogamontic" conjugation.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In some groups, partners are different in size and shape.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] This is referred to as "anisogamontic" conjugation.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In sessile peritrichs, for instance, one sexual partner (the microconjugant) is small and mobile, while the other (macroconjugant) is large and sessile.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The micronuclei undergo meiosis, producing four haploid micronuclei per cell.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Three of these micronuclei disintegrate.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The micronuclei in each cell fuse, forming a diploid micronucleus.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Mitosis occurs three times, giving rise to eight micronuclei.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Four of the new micronuclei transform into macronuclei, and the old macronucleus disintegrates.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Binary fission occurs twice, yielding four identical daughter cells.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Ciliates contain two types of nuclei: somatic "macronucleus" and the germline "micronucleus".
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Only the DNA in the micronucleus is passed on during sexual reproduction (conjugation).
[src:ciliate/ciliate] On the other hand, only the DNA in the macronucleus is actively expressed and results in the phenotype of the organism.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Macronuclear DNA is derived from micronuclear DNA by extensive DNA rearrangement and amplification.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The macronucleus begins as a copy of the micronucleus.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The micronuclear chromosomes are fragmented into many smaller pieces and amplified to give many copies.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The resulting macronuclear chromosomes often contain only a single gene.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In *Tetrahymena*, the micronucleus has 10 chromosomes (five per haploid genome), while the macronucleus has over 20,000 chromosomes.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In addition, the micronuclear genes are interrupted by numerous "internal eliminated sequences" (IESs).
[src:ciliate/ciliate] During development of the macronucleus, IESs are deleted and the remaining gene segments, macronuclear destined sequences (MDSs), are spliced together to give the operational gene.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] *Tetrahymena* has about 6,000 IESs and about 15% of micronuclear DNA is eliminated during this process.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The process is guided by small RNAs and epigenetic chromatin marks.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] This process is guided by long RNAs derived from the parental macronucleus.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] More than 95% of micronuclear DNA is eliminated during spirotrich macronuclear development.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] ln clonal populations of *Paramecium*, aging occurs over successive generations leading to a gradual loss of vitality, unless the cell line is revitalized by conjugation or autogamy.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In *Paramecium tetraurelia*, the clonally aging line loses vitality and expires after about 200 fissions, if the cell line is not rejuvenated by conjugation or self-fertilization.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The basis for clonal aging was clarified by the transplantation experiments of Aufderheide in 1986 who demonstrated that the macronucleus, rather than the cytoplasm, is responsible for clonal aging.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Additional experiments by Smith-Sonneborn, Holmes and Holmes, and Gilley and Blackburn demonstrated that, during clonal aging, DNA damage increases dramatically.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Thus, DNA damage appears to be the cause of aging in *P. tetraurelia*.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Until recently, the oldest ciliate fossils known were tintinnids from the Ordovician period.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] In 2007, Li *et al.* published a description of fossil ciliates from the Doushantuo Formation, about 580 million years ago, in the Ediacaran period.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] These included two types of tintinnids and a possible ancestral suctorian.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] However, a later paper found these to instead be deformed acritarchs.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] A fossil *Vorticella* has been discovered inside a leech cocoon from the Triassic period, about 200 million years ago.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] According to the 2016 phylogenetic analysis, Mesodiniea is consistently found as the sister group to all other ciliates.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Additionally, two big sub-groups are distinguished inside subphylum Intramacronucleata: SAL (Spirotrichea+Armophorea+Litostomatea) and CONthreeP or Ventrata (Colpodea+Oligohymenophorea+Nassophorea+Phyllopharyngea+Plagiopylea+Prostomatea).
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The class Protocruziea is found as the sister group to Ventrata/CONthreeP.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The class Cariacotrichea was excluded from the analysis, but it was originally established as part of Intramacronucleata.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The odontostomatids were identified in 2018 as its own class Odontostomatea, related to Armophorea.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Several different classification schemes have been proposed for the ciliates.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] Some old classifications included Opalinidae in the ciliates.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The fundamental difference between multiciliate flagellates (e.g., hemimastigids, *Stephanopogon*, *Multicilia*, opalines) and ciliates is the presence of macronuclei in ciliates alone.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] The only member of the ciliate phylum known to be pathogenic to humans is *Balantidium coli*, which causes the disease balantidiasis.
[src:ciliate/ciliate] It is not pathogenic to the domestic pig, the primary reservoir of this pathogen.
